fisering for spill 2.Divisjon Tabell |work=Norwegian Ice Hockey Association |date=2006-07-24 |accessdate=2010-04-14 |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724081756/http://www.hockey.no/t2.asp?p=59584&x=1&a=172237 |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\n*{{note label|qualy73|c|c}}In the 1972\u201373 season, an elaborate system of qualifying rounds was used to expand the number of teams in the 1.&nbsp;divisjon from eight to ten. Manglerud Star placed second in the first round for 2.&nbsp;divisjon teams and were thus promoted to the 1.&nbsp;divisjon without further competition.\n*{{note label|mellomspill|d|d}}Mellomspillet was a one-time continuation league contested in 1984\u201385 between the six highest ranked teams in the 1. divisjon. Of these six teams, the top four qualified for the Semi-finals of the Norwegian Championship.\n*{{note label|rename90|e|e}}Before the 1990\u201391 season, the 1.&nbsp;divisjon was renamed Eliteserien. Correspondingly, the 2.&nbsp;divisjon (second tier) was renamed 1.&nbsp;divisjon, the 3.&nbsp;divisjon (third tier) was renamed 2.&nbsp;divisjon etc.\n*{{note label|elite2|f|f}}Between the 1990\u201391 season and the 1993\u201394 season, the Eliteserien was divided into two parts. After the first 18 games, the top eight teams qualified for the second half of the Eliteserien. The bottom two teams were relegated to the 1. divisjon and would compete for the right to play in the Eliteserien in the following season. In 1990\u201391, the results of both rounds were added up to produce one league champion; in the three following seasons, there were two champions per season.\n*{{note label|noties|g|g}}Beginning with the [[2002-03 Eliteserien season|2002\u201303]] season, all games in the Eliteserien have a winner. In addition, teams now receive three points for a win in regulation time, two points for a win in overtime and one point for a loss in overtime.\n*{{note label|totals|h|h}}Totals as of the completion of the [[2009\u201310 GET-ligaen season|2009\u201310]] season.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Norwegian ice hockey team seasons|Manglerud Star Ishockey seasons, List of]]\n[[Category:Manglerud Star Ishockey|Seasons]]\n", "text_old": "'' are a Norwegian club based in [[Oslo]]. They are members of the highest Norwegian ice hockey league, [[GET-ligaen|Eliteserien]] (known as [[GET-ligaen]] for sponsorship reasons). Manrud Star Ishockey are the ice hockey department of [[IL Manglerud Star]], a sports club founded in 1913. Originally known as Star, the club became known as Manglerud/Star after merging with Manglerud IL in 1964, and eventually Manglerud Star (without the [[Slash (punctuation)|slash]]).<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mshockey.no/sak/000150.asp |title=Manglerud Star 1913 |work=Manglerud Star Ishockey |accessdate=2010-04-14 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Ice hockey was included as an activity in 1967,<ref name=\"info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mshockey.no/sak/000027.asp |title=Klubbinfo, Historikk |work=Manglerud Star Ishockey |accessdate=2010-04-14 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> and is today one of two sports practised by the club, the other being [[association football|football]].<ref name=\"history\"/> As of [[2009-10 GET-ligaen season|2010]], they have completed twenty-nine seasons in the Eliteserien and have won 385 regular season games.\n\nManglerud Star achieved success in the early years of their existence thanks to a selection of talented young players who, after winning several youth and junior championships, brought the club into the highest division ahead of the 1973&ndash;74 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mshockey.no/sak/000029.asp |title=Da MS tok b\u00f8tta |work=Manglerud Star Ishockey |accessdate=2010-04-14 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> From then on and until the early 1980s, the club fought regularly for the League Championship, finishing the season as runners-up five times in a row from 1975 to 1979. In the playoffs, they were increasingly successful until finally winning back-to-back [[List of Norwegian ice hockey champions|Norwegian Championship]] titles in 1977 and 1978. After losing in the Finals against [[V\u00e5lerenga Ishockey|V\u00e5lerengen]] in 1982, a long period of decline ensued, culminating in relegation to the second level in the 1990&ndash;91 season. Having returned to the Eliteserien in 1993, Manglerud Star collaborated with [[Furuset Ishockey|Furuset]] and a group of investors to form the [[Spektrum Flyers]] franchise in 1994.<ref name=\"info\"/> When this effort collapsed after only two seasons, Manglerud Star chose to again compete as a team in their own right.\n\n==Seasons==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|bgcolor=\"#D0E7FF\"|<small>'''[[List of Norwegian ice hockey champions|Norwegian Champions]]</small>\n|bgcolor=\"#FFE6BD\"|<small>'''Regular Season Champions'''</small>\n|bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|<small>'''[[Promotion and relegation|Promoted]]'''</small>\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|<small>'''[[Promotion and relegation|Relegated]]'''</small>\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"10\"|Regular season{{ref label|key|a|a}}\n!colspan=\"8\"|Postseason{{ref label|key|a|a}}\n|-\n!GP\n!W\n!L\n!T\n!OTW\n!OTL\n!GF\n!GA\n!Pts\n!Finish\n!GP\n!W\n!L\n!T\n!GF\n!GA\n!Pts\n!Result\n|-\n!1969\u201370\n|'''3. divisjon\n|bgcolor=\"#FFE6BD\"|'''B\n|10\n|9\n|1\n|0\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|46\n|20\n|18\n|bgcolor=\"#FFE6BD\"|'''1st\n|5\n|4\n|1\n|0\n|16\n|10\n|8\n|align=left bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|'''Won''' 3.&nbsp;divisjon Championship{{ref label|qualy70|b|b}}\n|-\n!1970\u201371\n|2. divisjon\n|A\n|10\n|5\n|2\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|41\n|31\n|13\n|2nd\n|6\n|2\n|3\n|1\n|15\n|29\n|5\n|align=left|3rd in Qualifying for 1.&nbsp;divisjon\n|-\n!1971\u201372\n|2. divisjon\n|A\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!1972\u201373\n|2. divisjo