]]) ([[Furuset Ishockey|Furuset]])<br>Lost in '''Finals''', 6\u201316 ([[Two-legged tie|agg]]) ([[V\u00e5lerenga Ishockey|V\u00e5lerengen]])\n|-\n!1982\u201383\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|36\n|21\n|15\n|0\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|193\n|184\n|42\n|6th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!1983\u201384\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|28\n|12\n|11\n|5\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|133\n|111\n|29\n|5th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!rowspan=2|1984\u201385\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|18\n|9\n|8\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|104\n|90\n|19\n|6th\n|rowspan=2 colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n|Mellomspillet{{ref label|mellomspill|d|d}}\n|\n|10\n|4\n|6\n|0\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|44\n|61\n|8\n|5th\n|-\n!1985\u201386\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|36\n|15\n|18\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|158\n|162\n|33\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!1986\u201387\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|36\n|16\n|18\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|164\n|159\n|34\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!1987\u201388\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|36\n|11\n|23\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|137\n|184\n|24\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|9th\n|2\n|2\n|0\n|&mdash;\n|18\n|6\n|&mdash;\n|align=left bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|'''Won''' Qualifying for 1.&nbsp;divisjon, 18\u20136 ([[Two-legged tie|agg]]) (Lambertseter)\n|-\n!1988\u201389\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|36\n|11\n|20\n|5\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|158\n|183\n|27\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|9th\n|2\n|1\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|14\n|12\n|&mdash;\n|align=left bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|'''Won''' Qualifying for 1.&nbsp;divisjon, 14\u201312 ([[Two-legged tie|agg]]) ([[L\u00f8renskog IK|L\u00f8renskog]])\n|-\n!1989\u201390\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|36\n|11\n|22\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|152\n|172\n|25\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!rowspan=2|1990\u201391{{ref label|rename90|e|e}}\n|Eliteserien&nbsp;I{{ref label|elite2|f|f}}\n|\n|18\n|3\n|15\n|0\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|72\n|179\n|6\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|9th\n|rowspan=2 colspan=8|\n|-\n|1. divisjon&nbsp;II\n|\n|14\n|9\n|4\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|95\n|87\n|19\n|3rd\n|-\n!rowspan=2|1991\u201392\n|1. divisjon&nbsp;I\n|\n|18\n|9\n|7\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|88\n|62\n|20\n|5th\n|rowspan=2 colspan=8|\n|-\n|1. divisjon&nbsp;II\n|\n|14\n|6\n|6\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|64\n|60\n|14\n|5th\n|-\n!rowspan=2|1992\u201393\n|'''1. divisjon&nbsp;I\n|\n|18\n|14\n|4\n|0\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|122\n|56\n|28\n|bgcolor=\"#FFE6BD\"|'''1st\n|rowspan=2 colspan=8|\n|-\n|1. divisjon&nbsp;II\n|\n|14\n|10\n|3\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|89\n|58\n|23\n|bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|2nd\n|-\n!rowspan=2|1993\u201394\n|Eliteserien&nbsp;I\n|\n|18\n|5\n|9\n|4\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|63\n|85\n|14\n|8th\n|rowspan=2 colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n|Eliteserien&nbsp;II\n|\n|14\n|4\n|9\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|46\n|60\n|9\n|7th\n|-\n!1994\u201395\n|rowspan=2 colspan=20|''Manglerud Star's place in the Eliteserien was used by the [[Spektrum Flyers]]<ref name=\"info\"/>\n|-\n!1995\u201396\n|-\n!1996\u201397\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|36\n|13\n|21\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|127\n|179\n|28\n|7th\n|3\n|0\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|6\n|20\n|&mdash;\n|align=left|Lost in Quarter-finals, 0\u20133 ([[V\u00e5lerenga Ishockey|V\u00e5lerenga]])\n|-\n!1997\u201398\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|44\n|18\n|23\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|172\n|179\n|39\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!1998\u201399\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|44\n|15\n|24\n|5\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|140\n|159\n|35\n|8th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!1999\u20132000\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|38\n|12\n|25\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|105\n|155\n|25\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!|[[2000-01 Eliteserien season|2000\u201301]]\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|42\n|20\n|18\n|4\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|123\n|116\n|44\n|5th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!|[[2001-02 Eliteserien season|2001\u201302]]\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|42\n|14\n|20\n|8\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|112\n|134\n|36\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!|[[2002-03 Eliteserien season|2002\u201303]]{{ref label|noties|g|g}}\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|38\n|12\n|19\n|&mdash;\n|2\n|5\n|127\n|141\n|45\n|7th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!|[[2003-04 Eliteserien season|2003\u201304]]\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|42\n|4\n|37\n|&mdash;\n|0\n|1\n|80\n|235\n|13\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|10th\n|6\n|3\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|26\n|19\n|11\n|align=left|3rd in Qualifying for Eliteserien\n|-\n!2004\u201305\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|32\n|27\n|3\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|192\n|60\n|56\n|2nd\n|6\n|3\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|13\n|16\n|9\n|align=left bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|'''2nd''' in Qualifying for Eliteserien\n|-\n!|[[2005-06 UPC-ligaen season|2005\u201306]]\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|42\n|5\n|34\n|&mdash;\n|2\n|1\n|105\n|226\n|20\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|10th\n|6\n|3\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|25\n|17\n|9\n|align=left|3rd in Qualifying for Eliteserien\n|-\n!2006\u201307\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|30\n|22\n|5\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|192\n|59\n|47\n|3rd\n|6\n|1\n|5\n|&ndash;\n|12\n|17\n|4\n|align=left|4th in Qualifying for Eliteserien\n|-\n!2007\u201308\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|30\n|10\n|17\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|123\n|149\n|23\n|11th\n|colspan=8|Did not qualify\n|-\n!2008\u201309\n|1. divisjon\n|\n|30\n|26\n|3\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|217\n|52\n|53\n|2nd\n|6\n|4\n|2\n|&mdash;\n|33\n|19\n|12\n|align=left bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"|'''2nd''' in Qualifying for Eliteserien\n|-\n!|[[2009-10 GET-ligaen season|2009\u201310]]\n|Eliteserien\n|\n|48\n|16\n|24\n|&mdash;\n|3\n|5\n|133\n|154\n|59\n|7th\n|5\n|1\n|4\n|&mdash;\n|14\n|19\n|&mdash;\n|align=left|Lost in Quarter-finals, 1\u20134 ([[V\u00e5lerenga Ishockey|V\u00e5lerenga]])\n|-\n!colspan=3|Eliteserien totals{{ref label|totals|h|h}}\n!935\n!378\n!471\n!67\n!7\n!12\n!3,689\n!3,974\n!886\n!\n!74\n!36\n!34\n!4\n!309\n!297\n!73\n!10 playoff appearances\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n*{{note label|key|a|a}}Code explanation; '''GP'''&mdash;Games Played, '''W'''&mdash;Wins, '''L'''&mdash;Losses, '''T'''&mdash;Tied games, '''OTW'''&mdash;Overtime/Shootout wins, '''OTL'''&mdash;Overtime/Shootout losses, '''GF'''&mdash;Goals For, '''GA'''&mdash;Goals Against, '''Pts'''&mdash;Points\n*{{note label|qualy70|b|b}}Manglerud Star tied first with Skiold after four games, winning the replay 6\u20135 to claim the 3.&nbsp;divisjon Championship title and win promotion to the 2.&nbsp;divisjon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hockey.no/t2.asp?p=59584&x=1&a=172237 |title=Kvalifisering for spill 2.Divisjon Tabell |work=Norwegian Ice Hockey Association |date=2006-07-24 |accessdate=2010-04-14 |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724081756/http://www.hockey.no/t2.asp?p=59584&x=1&a=172237 |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\n*{{note label|qualy73|c|c}}In the 1972\u201373 season, an elaborate system of qualifying rounds was used to expand the number of teams in the 1.&nbsp;divisjon from eight to ten. Manglerud Star placed second in the first round for 2.&nbsp;divisjon teams and were thus promoted to the 1.&nbsp;divisjon without further competition.\n*{{note label|mellomspill|d|d}}Mellomspillet was a one-time continuation league contested in 1984\u201385 between the six highest ranked teams in the 1. divisjon. Of these six teams, the top four qualified for the Semi-finals of the Norwegian Championship.\n*{{note label|rename90|e|e}}Before the 1990\u201391 season, the 1.&nbsp;divisjon was renamed Eliteserien. Correspondingly, the 2.&nbsp;divisjon (second tier) was renamed 1.&nbsp;divisjon, the 3.&nbsp;divisjon (third tier) was renamed 2.&nbsp;divisjon etc.\n*{{note label|elite2|f|f}}Between the 1990\u201391 season and the 1993\u201394 season, the Eliteserien was divided into two parts. After the first 18 games, the top eight teams qualified for the second half of the Eliteserien. The bottom two teams were relegated to the 1. divisjon and would compete for the right to play in the Eliteserien in the following season. In 1990\u201391, the results of both rounds were added up to produce one league champion; in the three following seasons, there were two champions per season.\n*{{note label|noties|g|g}}Beginning with the [[2002-03 Eliteserien season|2002\u201303]] season, all games in the Eliteserien have a winner. In addition, teams now receive three points for a win in regulation time, two points for a win in overtime and one point for a loss in overtime.\n*{{note label|totals|h|h}}Totals as of the completion of the [[2009\u201310 GET-ligaen season|2009\u201310]] season.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Norwegian ice hockey team seasons|Manglerud Star Ishockey seasons, List of]]\n[[Category:Manglerud Star Ishockey|Seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors. Fix vandalism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Manglerud_Star_Ishockey_seasons"}
{"title_page": "Henriette Pressburg", "text_new": "{{short description|Mother of Karl Marx}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Henriette Pressburg\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1788|09|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nijmegen]], [[Netherlands]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1863|11|30|1788|09|20|df=y}}\n| death_place =  [[Trier]], [[Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine|Prussian Rhineland]]\n| nationality   = {{unbulleted list|Dutch, then Prussian}}\n| known_for = Mother of [[Karl Marx]]\n| spouse      = [[Heinrich Marx]] \n}}\n'''Henriette Pressburg''' (20 September 1788 \u2013 30 November 1863) later on marriage, '''Henriette Marx''', was the mother of the [[Socialism|socialist]] philosopher and economist [[Karl Marx]].\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Voorgevel - Nijmegen - 20167789 - RCE.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Synagogue in Nonnenstraat, Nijmegen, built in 1756.]]\n[[File:Trier BW 2011-09-22 18-02-16.JPG|160px|thumb|right|8, Simeonstrasse, Trier: home of Marx family 1819\u201342]]\n\nHenriette Pressburg,{{efn|Also spelt Presburg or Pre\u00dfburg}} was born on 20 September 1788 in [[Nijmegen]] in the [[Netherlands]]. She was the second of the five children of Isaac Heymans Pressburg (1747\u20131832) and [[Nanette Salomons Cohen]] (1754\u20131833).<ref name=Geni/> The Pressburgs were a prosperous family, with Isaac working as a textile merchant. They were prominent members of Nijmegen's growing Jewish community,{{efn|The number of Jews in the Nijmegen area: 1784: 270; 1809: 359; 1840: 506. Source: Jewish History Museum, Amsterdam.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijmegen Synagogue website|url=http://nignijmegen.nl/index.php?pagina=historie|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>}} living first in Nonnenstraat then, when Henriette was 19, in Grotestraat. Isaac was the [[hazzan|cantor]]{{efn|Some sources say Isaac was Rabbi of Nijmegen.<ref name=McLellan3/>}} of the [[synagogue]] in Nonnenstraat<ref name=\"wordpress\">{{cite web|url=https://gerritkurvers.wordpress.com/2016/03/19/de-14e-maart-en-de-familie-presburg/|title=De 14e maart en de familie Presburg|website=gerritkurvers|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> where his father, Hirschl (or Chaim) Pressburg, had been the rabbi.<ref name=DNB>{{Cite journal|title=Karl Marx |journal=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=37 |pages=57\u201358 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2004 |ISBN=0198613873}}</ref> There had been rabbis in the family for at least a century.<ref name=Wilson>{{Cite book|first= Edmund |last=Wilson|title=To the Finland Station|pages=115, 119 |date=1972 |edition=revised |publisher=Fontana }}</ref>\n\nHenriette Pressburg married Hirschel (later [[Heinrich Marx|Heinrich) Marx]] (1777\u20131838) on 22 November 1814 in the Nijmegen Synagogue,<ref name=Schoncke/> she receiving a twenty thousand guilder dowry. The couple moved to Heinrich's home town of [[Trier]] in the [[Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine|Prussian Rhineland]], where Heinrich worked successfully as a lawyer. Here they had nine children, four sons and five daughters, two sons dying when children.<ref name=Geni>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Henriette-Marx/6000000007037730477|title=Henriette Marx (Pre\u00dfburg) (1788 - 1863) - Genealogy|website=geni.com|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> Karl, their third child, was born on 5 May 1818. In 1819 the family moved to a ten-room property opposite the ancient Roman [[Porta Nigra]] gateway, where Henriette lived with her family for the next 23 years.<ref name=Wheen14/>\n\nIn about 1817 Henriette's husband changed his name from Hirschel to Heinrich and was baptised into the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran Church]], followed by their children in August 1824. Henriette was baptised in November 1825. These conversions resulted in a complete break with Heinrich's family - his father was the rabbi of Trier - although Henriette continued to maintain close contact with her family in the Netherlands,<ref name=DNB/> her fourth child Hermann being born during a return visit to Nijmegen in August 1819.<ref name=\"geni\">{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Hermann-Marx/6000000008435644003|title=Hermann Marx (1819 - 1842) - Genealogy|website=geni.com|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHeinrich contracted [[tuberculosis]] and died in May 1838,<ref name=Wheen29>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx|page=29 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> when Henriette still had six of their children living at home. Although quite wealthy due to her inheritance, the family lived quite frugally.\n\n==Relationship with Karl Marx==\n[[File:Marx1.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Karl Marx as a student, 1836]]\n\n[[Karl Marx|Karl]] was the third child and second son of Heinrich and Henriette Marx. Graduating from the Trier [[Gymnasium (Germany)|Gymnasium]] in 1835 at the age of seventeen, Karl enrolled in the [[University of Bonn]], before moving to the [[Humboldt University of Berlin|University of Berlin]]. Henriette became concerned with his lifestyle away from home, including his membership of a local drinking society in Bonn.<ref name=Wilson/> The health of her other children exacerbated Henriette's worries. While Karl was at University, her son Eduard, aged 11, died of tuberculosis, Karl showing signs of similar symptoms.{{efn|McLellan's biography states: \"[Karl] Marx seems to have suffered quite severely from the tendency to tuberculosis that killed so many of his family (Four of Karl Marx\u2019s siblings eventually died of tuberculosis). The following year his military service was put off 'because of weakness of the lungs and periodical vomiting of blood'.\"<ref name=McLellan22>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, p 22. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref>}} Her regular letters to Karl emphasised the importance of healthy living, she advising:\n\n\u201cyou must never regard cleanliness and order as something secondary, for health and cheerfulness depend upon them. Insist strictly that your rooms are scrubbed frequently and fix a definite time for it \u2013 and you, my dear Karl, have a weekly scrub with sponge and soap.\"<ref name=Wheen14/>\n\nAfter Karl wrote to his father admitting his lifestyle was affecting his health, she wrote: \"you must avoid everything that could make things worse, you must not get over-heated, not drink a lot of wine or coffee, and not eat anything pungent, a lot of pepper or other spices. You must not smoke any tobacco, not stay up too late in the evening and always rise early. Be careful, also not to catch cold and, dear Karl, do not dance until you are quite well again.\"<ref name=Wheen14>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx |pages=8\u201315 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref>\n\nKarl rarely seems to have replied to his family's letters or even visited them.<ref name=Wheen29/>\n\nWhile his lifestyle and profligacy with money{{efn|In November 1837 Heinrich wrote to his son Karl at Berlin University \u201cAs though we were made of gold, my gentleman son disposes of almost 700 thalers a single year \u2026 whereas the richest spend no more than 500.\u201d See McLellan, Karl Marx, A Biography, page 26}} had already created tensions with his parents, Karl's relationship with his mother deteriorated further in the years after his father's death in 1838, with his requests for advances on his expected inheritance dominating their relationship, which became increasingly icy and distant.<ref name=Wheen14/>\n\nKarl stayed in Trier for six weeks during 1842, after the death of his brother Hermann, and for the wedding of his sister Sophie. Things did not go well, with Karl referring to \u201cthe most disagreeable of family controversies. My family has put difficulties in my way which, despite their own prosperity, subject me to the most straitened circumstances.\u201d Disagreements led to Karl moving mid-stay from the family home to a guest house nearby.<ref name=McLellan40>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, p 40. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref> The following year Karl married [[Jenny von Westphalen]], neither Henriette, nor any other member of the Marx family, attending.<ref>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx|page=52 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref>\n\nOver the years he complained repeatedly that his mother did not want to help him out of his financial distress, and openly hoped for her demise in order to hasten receipt of his inheritance.{{efn|To Arnold Ruge \"I have fallen out with my family and, as long as my mother lives, I have no right to my inheritance\"<ref>Karl Marx to Arnold Ruge, 25 January 1843. ''Marx-Engels-Werke. Vol 27, p. 415.''</ref> and to Engels on the sudden death of Engels\u2019 mistress Mary Burns in January 1856, \"If only, instead of Mary, it had been my mother, who is full of physical infirmities anyway now, and has had her fair span of life.\"<ref name=Wilson/>}} Henriette's view was that he should do more to earn money, she commenting \"if only Karl had made Capital, instead of just writing about it\".{{efn|Recalled by Karl Marx in a letter to Engels in 1868. See McLellan, Karl Marx, A Biography, page 320}}\n\nShe did however pass funds to him from time to time, although things did not always go smoothly.  In 1848, while Karl was living in Brussels, she paid him 6,000 francs.  Suspecting that the funds might be intended to finance the revolutionary movement, the Belgian police asked the Trier authorities to question Henriette, they accepting her explanation that \"her son had long been asking for money for his family and this was an advance on his inheritance\".<ref name=McLellan173>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, pp 173-4. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref>\n\nExiled from Germany during the 1850s, Karl again visited Germany in 1861. While there, he spent two days with Henriette in Trier, who agreed to cancel several of his older debts,<ref name=Wheen248>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx|page=248 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> although on his next short visit in August 1862 she refused to give him anything.<ref name=Wheen253>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx |page=253 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> This was the last time Henriette saw her son, she dying fifteen months later. Karl travelled to Trier for the funeral.<ref name=Wheen265>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx |pages=265\u20136 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref>\n\n==Sophie Pressburg and Lion Philips==\n[[File:Sophie Presburg.jpg|thumb|right|Sophie Pressburg]]\nIn 1820 Henriette's younger sister Sophie Pressburg (1797\u20131854) married the tobacco merchant [[Lion Philips]] (1794\u20131866) in the Nijmegen synagogue, before moving to the Dutch town of [[Zaltbommel]]. After the death of their mother in June 1833, Henriette agreed that Lion Philips would act as trustee for their parents' legacy for the benefit of the whole family.<ref name=DNB/> Lion was also executor of Henriette's will.<ref name=McLellan297>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, pp 297-8. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref>\n\nThe Philips\u2019 family got on well with Karl Marx, their nephew. He occasionally stayed with them in Zaltbommel, regularly corresponded with Lion Philips and often borrowed money against his legacy, particularly after he moved to London in 1849.<ref name=Goedkoop>{{Cite book|first1=Hans |last1=Goedkoop |first2=Kees |last2=Zandvliet|title= IJzeren Eeuw|publisher= Walburg Press |location=Zutphen |date=2015 |ISBN=9789057303418}}</ref>\n\nLion and Sophie's son Frederik and grandson [[Gerard Philips|Gerard]] founded the [[Philips Electronics]] Company in 1891. Gerard's younger brother [[Anton Philips|Anton]] joined the running of the company in 1912.<ref name=Textor>{{cite web|url=http://wgff.de/krefeld/download/siewaever_nr23.pdf|date=1 January 2008|author=Klaus|title=Westdeutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienkunde e.V. Sitz K\u00f6ln - Bezirksgruppe Krefeld (''A walk through Nijmegen: A communist and founder of Philips have same roots.'' West German Family Research Society, Krefeld Journal nr 23, 1.1.2008)|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOf Henriette's brothers, David became a lawyer in Amsterdam and later in [[Paramaribo]] in [[Surinam (Dutch colony)|Surinam]] and Martin remained in Nijmegen in the tobacco trade.<ref name=Goedkoop/>\n\n==Beliefs and outlook ==\n[[Image:Louise Juta geb Marx.jpg|170px|thumb|right|[[Louise Juta]] in 1863. One of Henriette's surviving children, she emigrated to South Africa with her husband in 1853]]\nHenriette was the last of the family to be baptised, in November 1825, more than a year after her children and about eight years her husband. Brought up in an orthodox Jewish household, she appeared to be more attached to Jewish culture than her husband and may have maintained some Jewish customs and practices within the Protestant family.<ref name=McLellan3>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, pp 3-7. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref> She clearly remained more religious than her husband, telling friends \"Yes, \"I believe in God, not for God's sake, but for my own.\"<ref name=Orr/>\n\nHenriette was never completely at ease either in writing or in speaking [[High German languages|high German]],<ref name=DNB/> and biographers of Marx often describe Henriette as uneducated, and perhaps of modest intellect,{{efn|For example: \"a good mother without special intellectual gifts\" (Otto R\u00fchle, Karl Marx. Life and work, p 17. Avalun-Verlag. Dresden 1928.); an \"uneducated woman entirely concerned for her large household, who did not have the least understanding of her son's gift or inclination\" (Isaiah Berlin, Karl Marx: His Life and Environment, p 40. Oxford University Press, 1965.); \"not exactly an intellectual\" (Arnold K\u00fcnzli, Karl Marx. Eine Psychographie, p 53. Europa Verlag, Vienna 1966.); \"she was an uneducated - indeed only semi-literate - woman whose interests began and ended with her family.\" (Francis Wheen, Karl Marx, p 12. Fourth Estate, London, 2000.)}} a view partly based on her surviving letters written in ungrammatical German with little punctuation.<ref name=McLellan3/> However this flawed German may suggest that [[Yiddish]] was her mother tongue,<ref name=McLellan3/>{{efn|While Yiddish grammar has many similarities to German, many elements originate from Slavic languages, Hebrew and Aramaic. It uses a variant of the [[Hebrew alphabet]]. [http://www.dovidkatz.net/dovid/PDFLinguistics/2-1987-Grammar-Yiddish.pdf Dovid Katz, ''Grammar of the Yiddish Language'', Duckworth, London, 1987 {{ISBN|0-7156-2161-0}}]}} while her speech also reflected the fact that she grew up in the Netherlands and only moved to a German speaking city in her mid-twenties.<ref name=Orr>Lyndon Orr, [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/4693/4693-h/4693-h.htm#link2H_4_0024 ''Famous Affinities of History: The Romance of Devotion. The Story of Karl Marx''] 1912.)</ref> Indeed, she always felt something of a stranger in Trier, being both closely attached to her own family<ref name=McLellan3/> and the country of her birth.{{efn|For example, Henriette's children had frequent contact - both visits and correspondence - with her sister Sophie and her Dutch husband in the Dutch town of Zaltbommel. Of the four of her daughters who married, two - Sophie and [[Louise Juta|Louise]] - married Dutchmen}}\n\nClearly Henriette's main preoccupation was the care of her large family which, over the years, suffered illness and a number of bereavements, five of her nine children predeceasing her.{{efn|Of Henriette's children, Mauritz died at the age of three in 1819, and Eduard aged eleven in 1837. By 1842, with the death of Hermann at the age of 22, Karl was his sole surviving son. Two daughters, Henriette and Caroline, also died in their twenties. Four of the five deaths were due to tuberculosis.<ref name=Geni/><ref name=\"famechain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famechain.com/family-tree/34934/heinrich-marx/henrietta-marx|title=Heinrich Marx &amp; Henrietta Marx Married, Children, Joint Family Tree &amp; History|website=FameChain|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>}} She admitted to having \"excessive mother love\", confirmed by Heinrich who wrote to their son Karl that \"you know your mother and how anxious she is.\"<ref name=Wheen14/> Her daughters described her in positive terms, Emilie saying that her \"dear mother enjoyed life and was an angel in going without if necessary and in dealing with family bereavement\",<ref>Emile Conradi (n\u00e9e Marx) to Babette Blum, 9 November 1865. (Bernhard Wachstein: Die Abstammung von Karl Marx, p 278. Copenhagen 1923.)</ref> while Sophie described her as \"small and delicate, and very intelligent. After all, she was a good housekeeper, who knew how to manage her inheritance and left her children with a greater sum than she herself inherited. She handled money better than her famous son Karl Marx.\u2019\u2019<ref name=Schoncke>Marx family documents: Henriette Presburg (1814) & Sophia Schmalhausen (n\u00e9e Marx) 1883.(Manfred Sch\u00f6ncke: Karl und Heinrich Marx und ihre Geschwister. pp 140\u20131 & 554. K\u00f6ln 1993. {{ISBN|9783891441855}})</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nHenriette Marx continued to live in Trier, where she died on 30 November 1863, aged 75.{{efn|On hearing the news of his mother's death, Karl commented \u201cFate laid claim to one of our family. I myself already have one foot in the grave. Circumstances being what they were, I, presumably, was needed here more than my mother.\u201d <ref name=Wheen265/>}} She was buried at the Protestant cemetery after a service at the Lutheran Church of the Redeemer.<ref>Manfred Sch\u00f6ncke: Karl und Heinrich Marx und ihre Geschwister. p. 762 ff. K\u00f6ln 1993. {{ISBN|3-89144-185-1}}</ref> She left her four surviving children substantial legacies, although much of Karl's share was paid to his Uncle Lion Philips in settlement of his debts.<ref name=Wheen265/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Karl Marx}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pressburg, Henriette}}\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:German people of Dutch-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Converts to Lutheranism from Judaism]]\n[[Category:Karl Marx]]\n[[Category:People from Nijmegen]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mother of Karl Marx}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Henriette Pressburg\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1788|09|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nijmegen]], [[Netherlands]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1863|11|30|1788|09|20|df=y}}\n| death_place =  [[Trier]], [[Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine|Prussian Rhineland]]\n| nationality   = {{unbulleted list|Dutch, then Prussian}}\n| known_for = Mother of [[Karl Marx]]\n| spouse      = [[Heinrich Marx]] \n}}\n'''Henriette Pressburg''' (20 September 1788 \u2013 30 November 1863) later on marriage, '''Henriette Marx''', was the mother of the [[Socialism|socialist]] philosopher and economist [[Karl Marx]].\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Voorgevel - Nijmegen - 20167789 - RCE.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Synagogue in Nonnenstraat, Nijmegen, built in 1756.]]\n[[File:Trier BW 2011-09-22 18-02-16.JPG|160px|thumb|right|8, Simeonstrasse, Trier: home of Marx family 1819\u201342]]\n\nHenriette Pressburg,{{efn|Also spelt Presburg or Pre\u00dfburg}} was born on 20 September 1788 in [[Nijmegen]] in the [[Netherlands]]. She was the second of the five children of Isaac Heymans Pressburg (1747\u20131832) and [[Nanette Salomons Cohen]] (1754\u20131833).<ref name=Geni/> The Pressburgs were a prosperous family, with Isaac working as a textile merchant. They were prominent members of Nijmegen's growing Jewish community,{{efn|The number of Jews in the Nijmegen area: 1784: 270; 1809: 359; 1840: 506. Source: Jewish History Museum, Amsterdam.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijmegen Synagogue website|url=http://nignijmegen.nl/index.php?pagina=historie|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>}} living first in Nonnenstraat then, when Henriette was 19, in Grotestraat. Isaac was the [[hazzan|cantor]]{{efn|Some sources say Isaac was Rabbi of Nijmegen.<ref name=McLellan3/>}} of the [[synagogue]] in Nonnenstraat<ref name=\"wordpress\">{{cite web|url=https://gerritkurvers.wordpress.com/2016/03/19/de-14e-maart-en-de-familie-presburg/|title=De 14e maart en de familie Presburg|website=gerritkurvers|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> where his father, Hirschl (or Chaim) Pressburg, had been the rabbi.<ref name=DNB>{{Cite journal|title=Karl Marx |journal=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=37 |pages=57\u201358 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2004 |ISBN=0198613873}}</ref> There had been rabbis in the family for at least a century.<ref name=Wilson>{{Cite book|first= Edmund |last=Wilson|title=To the Finland Station|page=115, 119 |date=1972 |edition=revised |publisher=Fontana }}</ref>\n\nHenriette Pressburg married Hirschel (later [[Heinrich Marx|Heinrich) Marx]] (1777\u20131838) on 22 November 1814 in the Nijmegen Synagogue,<ref name=Schoncke/> she receiving a twenty thousand guilder dowry. The couple moved to Heinrich's home town of [[Trier]] in the [[Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine|Prussian Rhineland]], where Heinrich worked successfully as a lawyer. Here they had nine children, four sons and five daughters, two sons dying when children.<ref name=Geni>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Henriette-Marx/6000000007037730477|title=Henriette Marx (Pre\u00dfburg) (1788 - 1863) - Genealogy|website=geni.com|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> Karl, their third child, was born on 5 May 1818. In 1819 the family moved to a ten-room property opposite the ancient Roman [[Porta Nigra]] gateway, where Henriette lived with her family for the next 23 years.<ref name=Wheen14/>\n\nIn about 1817 Henriette's husband changed his name from Hirschel to Heinrich and was baptised into the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran Church]], followed by their children in August 1824. Henriette was baptised in November 1825. These conversions resulted in a complete break with Heinrich's family - his father was the rabbi of Trier - although Henriette continued to maintain close contact with her family in the Netherlands,<ref name=DNB/> her fourth child Hermann being born during a return visit to Nijmegen in August 1819.<ref name=\"geni\">{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Hermann-Marx/6000000008435644003|title=Hermann Marx (1819 - 1842) - Genealogy|website=geni.com|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHeinrich contracted [[tuberculosis]] and died in May 1838,<ref name=Wheen29>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx|page=29 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> when Henriette still had six of their children living at home. Although quite wealthy due to her inheritance, the family lived quite frugally.\n\n==Relationship with Karl Marx==\n[[File:Marx1.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Karl Marx as a student, 1836]]\n\n[[Karl Marx|Karl]] was the third child and second son of Heinrich and Henriette Marx. Graduating from the Trier [[Gymnasium (Germany)|Gymnasium]] in 1835 at the age of seventeen, Karl enrolled in the [[University of Bonn]], before moving to the [[Humboldt University of Berlin|University of Berlin]]. Henriette became concerned with his lifestyle away from home, including his membership of a local drinking society in Bonn.<ref name=Wilson/> The health of her other children exacerbated Henriette's worries. While Karl was at University, her son Eduard, aged 11, died of tuberculosis, Karl showing signs of similar symptoms.{{efn|McLellan's biography states: \"[Karl] Marx seems to have suffered quite severely from the tendency to tuberculosis that killed so many of his family (Four of Karl Marx\u2019s siblings eventually died of tuberculosis). The following year his military service was put off 'because of weakness of the lungs and periodical vomiting of blood'.\"<ref name=McLellan22>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, p 22. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref>}} Her regular letters to Karl emphasised the importance of healthy living, she advising:\n\n\u201cyou must never regard cleanliness and order as something secondary, for health and cheerfulness depend upon them. Insist strictly that your rooms are scrubbed frequently and fix a definite time for it \u2013 and you, my dear Karl, have a weekly scrub with sponge and soap.\"<ref name=Wheen14/><br>\n\nAfter Karl wrote to his father admitting his lifestyle was affecting his health, she wrote: \"you must avoid everything that could make things worse, you must not get over-heated, not drink a lot of wine or coffee, and not eat anything pungent, a lot of pepper or other spices. You must not smoke any tobacco, not stay up too late in the evening and always rise early. Be careful, also not to catch cold and, dear Karl, do not dance until you are quite well again.\"<ref name=Wheen14>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx |pages=8\u201315 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> \n\nKarl rarely seems to have replied to his family's letters or even visited them.<ref name=Wheen29/> \n\nWhile his lifestyle and profligacy with money{{efn|In November 1837 Heinrich wrote to his son Karl at Berlin University \u201cAs though we were made of gold, my gentleman son disposes of almost 700 thalers a single year \u2026 whereas the richest spend no more than 500.\u201d See McLellan, Karl Marx, A Biography, page 26}} had already created tensions with his parents, Karl's relationship with his mother deteriorated further in the years after his father's death in 1838, with his requests for advances on his expected inheritance dominating their relationship, which became increasingly icy and distant.<ref name=Wheen14/> \n\nKarl stayed in Trier for six weeks during 1842, after the death of his brother Hermann, and for the wedding of his sister Sophie. Things did not go well, with Karl referring to \u201cthe most disagreeable of family controversies. My family has put difficulties in my way which, despite their own prosperity, subject me to the most straitened circumstances.\u201d Disagreements led to Karl moving mid-stay from the family home to a guest house nearby.<ref name=McLellan40>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, p 40. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref> The following year Karl married [[Jenny von Westphalen]], neither Henriette, nor any other member of the Marx family, attending.<ref>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx|page=52 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref>\n\nOver the years he complained repeatedly that his mother did not want to help him out of his financial distress, and openly hoped for her demise in order to hasten receipt of his inheritance.{{efn|To Arnold Ruge \"I have fallen out with my family and, as long as my mother lives, I have no right to my inheritance\"<ref>Karl Marx to Arnold Ruge, 25 January 1843. ''Marx-Engels-Werke. Vol 27, p. 415.''</ref> and to Engels on the sudden death of Engels\u2019 mistress Mary Burns in January 1856, \"If only, instead of Mary, it had been my mother, who is full of physical infirmities anyway now, and has had her fair span of life.\"<ref name=Wilson/>}} Henriette's view was that he should do more to earn money, she commenting \"if only Karl had made Capital, instead of just writing about it\".{{efn|Recalled by Karl Marx in a letter to Engels in 1868. See McLellan, Karl Marx, A Biography, page 320}} \n\nShe did however pass funds to him from time to time, although things did not always go smoothly.  In 1848, while Karl was living in Brussels, she paid him 6,000 francs.  Suspecting that the funds might be intended to finance the revolutionary movement, the Belgian police asked the Trier authorities to question Henriette, they accepting her explanation that \"her son had long been asking for money for his family and this was an advance on his inheritance\".<ref name=McLellan173>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, pp 173-4. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref> \n\nExiled from Germany during the 1850s, Karl again visited Germany in 1861. While there, he spent two days with Henriette in Trier, who agreed to cancel several of his older debts,<ref name=Wheen248>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx|page=248 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> although on his next short visit in August 1862 she refused to give him anything.<ref name=Wheen253>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx |page=253 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref> This was the last time Henriette saw her son, she dying fifteen months later. Karl travelled to Trier for the funeral.<ref name=Wheen265>{{Cite book|first=Francis |last=Wheen|title=Karl Marx |pages=265\u20136 |publisher=Fourth Estate |date=1999 |ISBN=9781841151144}}</ref>\n\n==Sophie Pressburg and Lion Philips==\n[[File:Sophie Presburg.jpg|thumb|right|Sophie Pressburg]]\nIn 1820 Henriette's younger sister Sophie Pressburg (1797\u20131854) married the tobacco merchant [[Lion Philips]] (1794\u20131866) in the Nijmegen synagogue, before moving to the Dutch town of [[Zaltbommel]]. After the death of their mother in June 1833, Henriette agreed that Lion Philips would act as trustee for their parents' legacy for the benefit of the whole family.<ref name=DNB/> Lion was also executor of Henriette's will.<ref name=McLellan297>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, pp 297-8. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref>\n\nThe Philips\u2019 family got on well with Karl Marx, their nephew. He occasionally stayed with them in Zaltbommel, regularly corresponded with Lion Philips and often borrowed money against his legacy, particularly after he moved to London in 1849.<ref name=Goedkoop>{{Cite book|first1=Hans |last1=Goedkoop |first2=Kees |last2=Zandvliet|title= IJzeren Eeuw|publisher= Walburg Press |location=Zutphen |date=2015 |ISBN=9789057303418}}</ref> \n\nLion and Sophie's son Frederik and grandson [[Gerard Philips|Gerard ]] founded the [[Philips Electronics]] Company in 1891. Gerard's younger brother [[Anton Philips|Anton]] joined the running of the company in 1912.<ref name=Textor>{{cite web|url=http://wgff.de/krefeld/download/siewaever_nr23.pdf|date=1 January 2008|author=Klaus|title=Westdeutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienkunde e.V. Sitz K\u00f6ln - Bezirksgruppe Krefeld (''A walk through Nijmegen: A communist and founder of Philips have same roots.'' West German Family Research Society, Krefeld Journal nr 23, 1.1.2008)|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOf Henriette's brothers, David became a lawyer in Amsterdam and later in [[Paramaribo]] in [[Surinam (Dutch colony)|Surinam]] and Martin remained in Nijmegen in the tobacco trade.<ref name=Goedkoop/>\n\n==Beliefs and outlook ==\n[[Image:Louise Juta geb Marx.jpg|170px|thumb|right|[[Louise Juta]] in 1863. One of Henriette's surviving children, she emigrated to South Africa with her husband in 1853]]\nHenriette was the last of the family to be baptised, in November 1825, more than a year after her children and about eight years her husband. Brought up in an orthodox Jewish household, she appeared to be more attached to Jewish culture than her husband and may have maintained some Jewish customs and practices within the Protestant family.<ref name=McLellan3>David McLellan. Karl Marx: A biography, pp 3-7. London 1973/1995 {{ISBN|9780333639474}}.</ref> She clearly remained more religious than her husband, telling friends \"Yes, \"I believe in God, not for God's sake, but for my own.\"<ref name=Orr/>\n\nHenriette was never completely at ease either in writing or in speaking [[High German languages|high German]],<ref name=DNB/> and biographers of Marx often describe Henriette as uneducated, and perhaps of modest intellect,{{efn|For example: \"a good mother without special intellectual gifts\" (Otto R\u00fchle, Karl Marx. Life and work, p 17. Avalun-Verlag. Dresden 1928.); an \"uneducated woman entirely concerned for her large household, who did not have the least understanding of her son's gift or inclination\" (Isaiah Berlin, Karl Marx: His Life and Environment, p 40. Oxford University Press, 1965.); \"not exactly an intellectual\" (Arnold K\u00fcnzli, Karl Marx. Eine Psychographie, p 53. Europa Verlag, Vienna 1966.); \"she was an uneducated - indeed only semi-literate - woman whose interests began and ended with her family.\" (Francis Wheen, Karl Marx, p 12. Fourth Estate, London, 2000.)}} a view partly based on her surviving letters written in ungrammatical German with little punctuation.<ref name=McLellan3/> However this flawed German may suggest that [[Yiddish]] was her mother tongue,<ref name=McLellan3/>{{efn|While Yiddish grammar has many similarities to German, many elements originate from Slavic languages, Hebrew and Aramaic. It uses a variant of the [[Hebrew alphabet]]. [http://www.dovidkatz.net/dovid/PDFLinguistics/2-1987-Grammar-Yiddish.pdf Dovid Katz, ''Grammar of the Yiddish Language'', Duckworth, London, 1987 {{ISBN|0-7156-2161-0}}]}} while her speech also reflected the fact that she grew up in the Netherlands and only moved to a German speaking city in her mid-twenties.<ref name=Orr>Lyndon Orr, [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/4693/4693-h/4693-h.htm#link2H_4_0024 ''Famous Affinities of History: The Romance of Devotion. The Story of Karl Marx''] 1912.)</ref> Indeed, she always felt something of a stranger in Trier, being both closely attached to her own family<ref name=McLellan3/> and the country of her birth.{{efn|For example, Henriette's children had frequent contact - both visits and correspondence - with her sister Sophie and her Dutch husband in the Dutch town of Zaltbommel. Of the four of her daughters who married, two - Sophie and [[Louise Juta|Louise]] - married Dutchmen}} \n\nClearly Henriette's main preoccupation was the care of her large family which, over the years, suffered illness and a number of bereavements, five of her nine children predeceasing her.{{efn|Of Henriette's children, Mauritz died at the age of three in 1819, and Eduard aged eleven in 1837. By 1842, with the death of Hermann at the age of 22, Karl was his sole surviving son. Two daughters, Henriette and Caroline, also died in their twenties. Four of the five deaths were due to tuberculosis.<ref name=Geni/><ref name=\"famechain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famechain.com/family-tree/34934/heinrich-marx/henrietta-marx|title=Heinrich Marx &amp; Henrietta Marx Married, Children, Joint Family Tree &amp; History|website=FameChain|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>}} She admitted to having \"excessive mother love\", confirmed by Heinrich who wrote to their son Karl that \"you know your mother and how anxious she is.\"<ref name=Wheen14/> Her daughters described her in positive terms, Emilie saying that her \"dear mother enjoyed life and was an angel in going without if necessary and in dealing with family bereavement\",<ref>Emile Conradi (n\u00e9e Marx) to Babette Blum, 9 November 1865. (Bernhard Wachstein: Die Abstammung von Karl Marx, p 278. Copenhagen 1923.)</ref> while Sophie described her as \"small and delicate, and very intelligent. After all, she was a good housekeeper, who knew how to manage her inheritance and left her children with a greater sum than she herself inherited. She handled money better than her famous son Karl Marx.\u2019\u2019<ref name=Schoncke>Marx family documents: Henriette Presburg (1814) & Sophia Schmalhausen (n\u00e9e Marx) 1883.(Manfred Sch\u00f6ncke: Karl und Heinrich Marx und ihre Geschwister. pp 140\u20131 & 554. K\u00f6ln 1993. {{ISBN|9783891441855}})</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nHenriette Marx continued to live in Trier, where she died on 30 November 1863, aged 75.{{efn|On hearing the news of his mother's death, Karl commented \u201cFate laid claim to one of our family. I myself already have one foot in the grave. Circumstances being what they were, I, presumably, was needed here more than my mother.\u201d <ref name=Wheen265/>}} She was buried at the Protestant cemetery after a service at the Lutheran Church of the Redeemer.<ref>Manfred Sch\u00f6ncke: Karl und Heinrich Marx und ihre Geschwister. p. 762 ff. K\u00f6ln 1993. {{ISBN|3-89144-185-1}}</ref> She left her four surviving children substantial legacies, although much of Karl's share was paid to his Uncle Lion Philips in settlement of his debts.<ref name=Wheen265/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pressburg, Henriette}}\n{{Karl Marx}}\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:German people of Dutch-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Converts to Lutheranism from Judaism]]\n[[Category:Karl Marx]]\n[[Category:People from Nijmegen]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henriette_Pressburg"}
